      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Pectin is a naturally occurring polysaccharide (complex carbohydrate) found in the cell walls of all land plants. In the food industry, commercial pectin is primarily extracted from citrus peels (lemon, lime, orange — approximately 70% of global production) and apple pomace (the leftover pulp after juicing — approximately 25% of production). The extraction process involves heating the fruit peels in acidified water, filtering the solution, and then precipitating the pectin with alcohol. The resulting powder is classified as either "high-methoxyl" (HM) pectin, which requires sugar and acid to gel, or "low-methoxyl" (LM) pectin, which gels with calcium ions and is used in sugar-free products. Most gummy candy uses HM pectin because the high sugar content of candy provides ideal gelling conditions.' },
