      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'High-methoxyl (HM) pectin requires high sugar content (at least 55% by weight) and an acidic environment (pH 3.0-3.5) to form a gel. It is used in traditional gummy candy where sugar is abundant. Low-methoxyl (LM) pectin gels with calcium ions instead of sugar, making it suitable for sugar-free and reduced-sugar gummies. LM pectin produces a softer, more fragile gel than HM pectin, which is why sugar-free pectin gummies often have a different texture than their full-sugar counterparts. SmartSweets uses a modified pectin-fiber blend with allulose, which behaves differently from both traditional HM and LM systems. The choice of pectin type is one of the key decisions candy formulators make when developing new products.' },
