    <h2 id="making-pectin-gummies">How Pectin Gummies Are Made: The Factory Process</h2>

    <p>Understanding how pectin gummies are manufactured explains why they taste and feel the way they do — and why the manufacturing process matters for quality. Modern pectin gummy production uses a method called starch-mogul casting, a technique borrowed from traditional gelatin candy manufacturing but adapted for pectin's unique gelling requirements.</p>

    <div class="num-steps">
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Slurry preparation.</strong> Pectin powder is dry-mixed with a portion of the sugar to prevent clumping, then dissolved in hot water (175-195°F / 80-90°C) with constant stirring. The pectin must fully hydrate — any undissolved pectin particles create texture defects in the final product.</li>
        <li><strong>Cooking.</strong> The pectin solution is combined with the remaining sugar, glucose syrup, and acid (citric or tartaric) and cooked to 225-240°F (107-116°C) to reach the target solids content (78-82% for gummy candy). Higher cooking temperatures produce firmer gummies.</li>
        <li><strong>Flavor and color addition.</strong> After cooking, the mixture is cooled slightly (to approximately 195°F / 90°C) before adding natural flavors and colors. High temperatures would destroy volatile flavor compounds and degrade heat-sensitive natural pigments.</li>
        <li><strong>Starch-mogul depositing.</strong> The hot pectin mixture is deposited into cavities stamped into trays of dry corn starch using a mogul machine. The starch absorbs moisture from the surface of the gummies, forming the characteristic matte finish and preventing sticking.</li>
        <li><strong>Curing and drying.</strong> Trays are held in a conditioning room at controlled temperature and humidity for 24-72 hours. During this time, the pectin gel network fully sets, excess moisture migrates out, and the gummies develop their final texture. This step is critical — rushing it produces gummies that are too soft.</li>
        <li><strong>Finishing.</strong> Cured gummies are tumbled to remove residual starch, then coated with a thin layer of carnauba wax or vegetable oil to prevent sticking in the bag. Some brands apply a sour coating (citric acid + sugar) at this stage. The finished gummies are then weighed, bagged, and sealed.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

