    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Pectin Gummy Candy</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is pectin and where does it come from?</summary>
      <p>Pectin is a polysaccharide found in all plant cell walls. Commercial pectin is extracted from citrus peels (~70% of production) and apple pomace (~25%) using hot acidified water. It is classified as HM (high-methoxyl, gels with sugar + acid) or LM (low-methoxyl, gels with calcium ions). Most gummy candy uses HM pectin.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why do pectin gummies feel different from gelatin gummies?</summary>
      <p>Gelatin melts at body temperature, creating a gradual dissolve sensation. Pectin breaks through chewing force rather than melting, producing a cleaner, quicker "break" with faster flavor release. Modern pectin-starch blends have narrowed this texture gap significantly.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is pectin healthier than gelatin?</summary>
      <p>In candy amounts, neither provides significant nutrition. Pectin is a soluble fiber; gelatin is a protein with glycine and proline. The real advantage of pectin is dietary compatibility — vegan, halal, and kosher friendly. Brands using pectin also tend to use cleaner overall ingredients.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can you make pectin gummies at home?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Mix 1 cup fruit juice with 1/2 cup sugar, 3-4 tablespoons HM pectin powder, and 1/4 teaspoon citric acid. Heat until dissolved, boil 1 minute, pour into silicone molds, and refrigerate 2-4 hours. Homemade versions will be softer than commercial gummies.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do pectin gummies expire faster than gelatin gummies?</summary>
      <p>Slightly. Pectin gummies last 9-14 months vs. 12-18 months for gelatin. Pectin is more susceptible to moisture migration and has a lower heat threshold. Store below 75°F in airtight containers for best shelf life.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are pectin gummies better for the environment?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Pectin is extracted from agricultural waste (citrus peels, apple pomace), while gelatin requires animal farming. A 2022 life cycle assessment found pectin production generates 60-70% fewer greenhouse gas emissions per kilogram than gelatin production.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between HM and LM pectin in gummies?</summary>
      <p>HM pectin (DE &gt;50%) requires sugar and acid to gel — used in full-sugar gummies. LM pectin (DE &lt;50%) gels with calcium ions — used in sugar-free and reduced-sugar gummies. HM produces firmer gels; LM produces softer, more fragile gels.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why are pectin gummies more expensive than gelatin gummies?</summary>
      <p>Pectin costs $15-25/kg vs. $5-10/kg for gelatin due to more complex extraction. Pectin requires tighter manufacturing controls (temperature, pH). Brands using pectin also tend to invest in organic certification and premium ingredients, further increasing retail prices.</p>
    </details>

